# VAK_3b — VAkK_3.20

## Sanskrit — Devanāgarī

स प्रतीत्यसमुत्पादो द्वादशाङ्गस्त्रिकाण्डकः ।
पूर्वापरान्तयोर्द्वे द्वे मध्येऽष्टौ परिपूरिणः ॥ VAkK_3.20 ॥

## Sanskrit — IAST

sa pratītyasamutpādo dvādaśāṅgas trikāṇḍakaḥ /
pūrvāparāntayor dve dve madhye ’ṣṭau paripūriṇaḥ // VAkK_3.20 //

Sandhi note: source form dvādaśāṅgastrikāṇḍakaḥ is resolved as dvādaśa-aṅgaḥ trikāṇḍakaḥ.

## Padaccheda

| Sandhi form | Padaccheda | Basic meaning |
|---|---|---|
| sa | saḥ | that; this one |
| pratītyasamutpādaḥ | pratītya-samutpādaḥ | dependent co-arising |
| dvādaśāṅgaḥ | dvādaśa-aṅgaḥ | twelve-limbed; having twelve members |
| trikāṇḍakaḥ | tri-kāṇḍakaḥ | three-sectioned; consisting of three divisions |
| pūrvāparāntayoḥ | pūrva-apara-antayoḥ | of the former and latter limits / ends |
| dve dve | dve dve | two and two |
| madhye | madhye | in the middle |
| aṣṭau | aṣṭau | eight |
| paripūriṇaḥ | paripūriṇaḥ | completing; fulfilling; making complete |

## Literal Translation

This dependent co-arising is twelve-limbed and three-sectioned: at the former and latter limits there are two each, and in the middle eight, completing it.

## Philosophical Translation

This dependent co-arising is the twelvefold structure of conditioned becoming, articulated into three sections: two determinations at the prior limit, two at the subsequent limit, and eight in the middle that complete the presently manifest process.

## Technical Vocabulary

| Sanskrit | Working translation | Note |
|---|---|---|
| pratītyasamutpāda | dependent co-arising | Not merely causation; a structured arising through dependence |
| aṅga | limb / member | A functional determination in the cycle |
| dvādaśāṅga | twelve-limbed | The twelvefold chain |
| kāṇḍa | section / division | A doctrinal articulation of the twelve limbs |
| trikāṇḍaka | three-sectioned | The twelve are divided across prior, middle, later |
| pūrvānta | prior limit | Former temporal boundary |
| aparānta | later limit | Future temporal boundary |
| madhya | middle | Present-life unfolding |
| paripūriṇa | completing / fulfilling | The middle eight complete the concrete process |

## Doctrinal Structure

VAkK_3.20 gives the formal schema before naming the twelve links in 3.21–3.24.

```text
Prior limit
    2 limbs

Middle
    8 limbs

Later limit
    2 limbs
```

The standard Abhidharma arrangement anticipated by this verse is:

```text
Prior limit:
    1. avidyā
    2. saṃskārāḥ

Middle:
    3. vijñāna
    4. nāmarūpa
    5. ṣaḍāyatana
    6. sparśa
    7. vedanā
    8. tṛṣṇā
    9. upādāna
    10. bhava

Later limit:
    11. jāti
    12. jarāmaraṇa
```

The verse itself does not yet list the limbs. It first gives the form of the system. VAkK_3.20 is therefore the architectonic verse.

## Logical Determination

This is not merely twelve causes. It is a structured syllogism of saṃsāric process.

```text
Prior condition
        ↓
Present completion
        ↓
Future result
```

More precisely:

```text
Pūrva-anta
    past ground

Madhya
    present concrete mediation

Apara-anta
    future consequence
```

The middle is the site of manifestation. The prior and later limits are not self-standing domains; they are grasped through the middle.

```text
Ground
    ↓
Mediation
    ↓
Result
```

The eight middle limbs complete the intelligibility of the abstract relation between past and future.

## Organon Interpretation

For VAK_3b, pratītyasamutpāda is the first full wheel-structure of Loka–Karma synthesis.

Earlier in Chapter 3:

```text
World
    domains
    births
    intermediate existence
    entry into womb
    beginningless becoming
```

At 3.20 this becomes formalized as:

```text
Dependent Co-Arising
    twelve-limbed
    three-sectioned
    completed in the middle
```

This is an Abhidharma semantic wheel:

```text
Past
    → Present
        → Future
```

But the present is not passive. It is the field where the whole structure is concretely intelligible.

```text
pūrvānta
    = inherited ground

madhya
    = manifest dataset / concrete process

aparānta
    = projected result
```

The deeper logic:

```text
Cause is not linear.
Cause is articulated as a wheel.
The wheel is intelligible only through its middle.
```

